In order to run ACE, LAMMPS needs to be compiled with -DPKG_ML-PACE=ON. The model `c_ace.yace` is fitted to uncorrected PBE data which does not include van der Waals interactions. A `D2` correction is to be added explicitly to model vdW. This is done by using `hybrid/overlay` pair_style in Lammps which essentially adds up the interactions (pace + D2).

pair_style              hybrid/overlay pace table linear 10000
pair_coeff              * * pace c_ace.yace C               # short range interactions modelled by ACE
pair_coeff              * * table d2.table D2 9.0          # long range D2 interactions given in d2.table

This way, one can choose the cutoff for the long range D2 interactions independently. One can experiment with the long-range cutoff or turn it off completely.

It is also possible to use the LAMMPS calculator in ASE in a similar way by defining a lammps ase-calc:
#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
from ase.calculators.lammpsrun import LAMMPS

model = "c_v3.yace"
d2_table = "d2.table"

os.environ["ASE_LAMMPSRUN_COMMAND"]="mpirun lmp_mpi"

calculator_lmp_params = {'mass': ['1 12.101'],
                         'pair_style': 'hybrid/overlay pace table linear 10000',
                         'pair_coeff': ["* * pace %s C"%model,"* * table %s D2 9.0"%d2_table],
                         'keep_tmp_files' : True}
calc = LAMMPS(**calculator_lmp_params)

#-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Note: For simulations where extremely short neighbour distances are expected to occur (<0.2 A), it is preferred to use `d2_short.table` instead.

